            <h2>Psychoeducational and Neuropsychological Evaluations</h2>
            <p> 
                <strong>
                    Which Evaluation Should I Choose for My Child?
                </strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                The choice of evaluations depends on the referral question. A neuropsychological evaluation is usually preferred when diagnostic information and intervention guidance are needed. When a child has already been diagnosed with a learning disability and only needs documentation for accommodations in school (such as extended time on tests), then a psychoeducational evaluation can be sufficient.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>What's the difference?</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                A psychoeducational assessment is a comprehensive evaluation of cognitive abilities, academic skills, and social-emotional functioning to understand a person’s learning profile and identify potential difficulties or strengths. It typically includes background information, cognitive and academic assessments, social-emotional and behavioral evaluations, interviews, and observations. Psychoeducational evaluations quantify difficulties in reading, writing, and math, helping to qualify students for school services and accommodations like extended test time.
            </p>
            <p>
                Neuropsychological evaluations provide deeper insights into how neurocognitive processes affect learning, explaining why a child struggles in school. While a psychoeducational evaluation is part of a broader neuropsychological evaluation in school-age children, neuropsychological evaluations more deeply into areas such as language, visual-perceptual skills, information processing, attention/executive functioning, memory, and psycho-emotional health. Understanding strengths and weaknesses allows for more tailored, individualized interventions.
            </p>
        </div>

